from nichael nichael cramer subject re some question from a new christian ofm respond to a query about reference work aside from a commentary you might also want to consider an introduction these be book intend for use in undergraduate bible course they give historical background discussion of literary style etc and generally they have good bibligraphy for further read i typically recommend kee froehlich and young nt introduction two other intro to consider the introduction by ku mmel be a translation of a strandard nt text the reference be slightly date and the style be somewhat dense but the book contain a wealth of information perrin and duling intro be also very good it somewhat more modern than ku mmel but not quite so densely pack also the author tend to go through the book of the nt in the historical order of composition thi gife a very useful perspective on the development of the nt there be also some good one-volume commentary probably the best recommendation these day would be harper bible commentary a slight dissent i think the harper be ok but not great one particular problem i have be that it tend to be pretty skimpy on bibliographic material my feel be that it be ok for quick look-up but not real useful for study in depth i keep a copy in my office at work i think there may be a couple of book with thi title so far a i know there be the only one book with thi exact title jame l may general editor harper and row although i think i recall a older series under the name harper commentary also there a separate harper bible dictionary most of my comment on the hc also apply to the hbd my favorite one-volume commentary be the new jerome biblical commentary the njbc be rather catholic in focu and somewhat bias toward the nt the reader can decide for her or himself whether these be pluse or minuse in any case the scholarship be by and large excellent note the njbc be a completely rework update version of the jerome biblical commentary copy of which can still be find on sale nichael 